1. What is the core difference between a class and an interface?

A class defines what an object is (identity + implementation), while an interface defines what an object
can do (contract + behavior). A class can only extend one superclass, but an interface allows a class
to follow multiple different behaviors.

2. Can interfaces have fields? If yes, what are the implicit modifiers for them?

Yes, interfaces can have fields. They are implicitly public, static, and final, meaning they act as constants
rather than instance variables.

3. Can a class implement multiple interfaces? Explain why this is useful.

Yes, a class can implement multiple interfaces. This is useful because it allows an object to play several
roles at once (like a Student being both a Movable object and a CanHavePizza eater) without the restrictions of
single inheritance.